August EighthEvents*1220 ;ndash; Sweden is defeated by Estonian tribes in the Battle of Lihula.*1503 ;ndash; King James IV of Scotland marries Margaret Tudor, daughter of King Henry VII of England at Holyrood Abbey in Edinburgh, Scotland.*1576 ;ndash; The cornerstone for Tycho Brahe's Uraniborg observatory is laid on the island of Hven.*1585 ;ndash; John Davis enters Cumberland Sound in search of the Northwest Passage.*1588 ;ndash; Anglo-Spanish War (1585–1604)|Anglo-Spanish War: Battle of Gravelines: The naval engagement ends, ending the Spanish Armada's attempt to invade England.*1605 ;ndash; The city of Oulu, Finland, is founded by Charles IX of Sweden.*1647 ;ndash; The Irish Confederate Wars and Wars of the Three Kingdoms: Battle of Dungan's Hill: English Parliamentary forces defeat Irish forces.*1709 ;ndash; Bartolomeu de Gusmão demonstrates the lifting power of hot air in an audience before the King of Portugal in Lisbon, Portugal*1786 ;ndash; Mont Blanc on the French – Italian border is climbed for the first time by Jacques Balmat and Dr. Michel-Gabriel Paccard.*1793 ;ndash; The insurrection of Lyon occurs during the French Revolution.*1794 ;ndash; Joseph Whidbey leads an expedition to search for the Northwest Passage near Juneau, Alaska.*1844 ;ndash; The Quorum of the Twelve Apostles, headed by Brigham Young, is reaffirmed as the leading body of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).*1863 ;ndash; American Civil War: Following his defeat in the Battle of Gettysburg, General Robert E. Lee sends a letter of resignation to Confederate President Jefferson Davis (which is refused upon receipt).*1870 ;ndash; The ''Republic of Ploiești'', a failed Radical-Liberal rising against Domnitor Carol of Romania.*1876 ;ndash; Thomas Edison receives a patent for his mimeograph.*1885 ;ndash; More than 1.5 million people attend the funeral of Ulysses S. Grant in New York City.*1908 ;ndash; Wilbur Wright makes his first flight at a racecourse at Le Mans, France. It is the Wright Brothers' first public flight.*1918 ;ndash; World War I: The Battle of Amiens begins a string of almost continuous victories with a push through the German front lines (Hundred Days Offensive).*1927 ;ndash; The predecessor to the Philippine Stock Exchange opens.*1929 ;ndash; The German airship ''Graf Zeppelin'' begins a round-the-world flight.*1940 ;ndash; The "Aufbau Ost" directive is signed by Wilhelm Keitel.*1942 ;ndash; Quit India Movement is launched in India against the British rule in response to Mohandas Gandhi's call for swaraj or complete independence.*1945 ;ndash; The London Charter is signed by France, the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union and the United States, establishing the laws and procedures for the Nuremberg trials.*1946 ;ndash; First flight of the Convair B-36, the world's first mass-produced nuclear weapon delivery vehicle, the heaviest mass-produced piston-engined aircraft, with the longest wingspan of any military aircraft, and the first bomber with intercontinental range.*1960 ;ndash; South Kasai secedes from the Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)|Congo.*1963 ;ndash; Great Train Robbery: In England, a gang of 15 train robbers steal Pound sterling|£2.6 million in bank notes.*  1963   ;ndash; The Zimbabwe African National Union (ZANU), the current ruling party of Zimbabwe, is formed by a split from the Zimbabwe African People's Union.*1967 ;ndash; The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) is founded by Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.*1969 ;ndash; At a zebra crossing in London, photographer Iain Macmillan takes the photo that becomes the cover of the Beatles album ''Abbey Road''.*1973 ;ndash; Kim Dae-jung, a South Korean politician and later president of South Korea, is kidnapped.*1974 ;ndash; President Richard Nixon, in a nationwide television address, announces his resignation from the office of the President of the United States effective noon the next day.*1980 ;ndash; The Central Hotel Fire occurs in Bundoran, Ireland.*1988 ;ndash; The "8888 Uprising" occurs in Burma.*1989 ;ndash; Space Shuttle program: STS-28 Mission: Space Shuttle Columbia takes off on a secret five-day military mission.*1990 ;ndash; Iraq occupies Kuwait and the state is annexed to Iraq. This would lead to the Gulf War shortly afterward.*1991 ;ndash; The Warsaw radio mast, at one time the tallest construction ever built, collapses.*1993 ;ndash; The 7.8 Mw Guam earthquake shakes the island with a maximum Mercalli intensity of IX (''Violent''), causing around United States dollar|$250 million in damage and injuring up to 71 people.*2000 ;ndash; Confederate submarine ''H.L. Hunley'' is raised to the surface after 136 years on the ocean floor and 30 years after its discovery by undersea explorer E. Lee Spence.*2007 ;ndash; An EF2 tornado touches down in Kings County and Richmond County, New York, the most powerful tornado in New York to date and the first in Brooklyn since 1889.*2008 ;ndash; A EuroCity express train en route from Kraków, Poland to Prague, Czech Republic 2008 Studénka train disaster|strikes a part of a motorway bridge that had fallen onto the railroad track near Studénka railway station in the Czech Republic and derails, killing eight people and injuring 64 others.*  2008   ;ndash; Official ceremony of 2008 Summer Olympic Games in Bird's Nest.*2010 ;ndash; 2010 China floods: A mudslide in Zhugqu County, Gansu, China, kills more than 1,400 people.*2013 ;ndash; A suicide bombing at a funeral in the Pakistani city of Quetta kills at least 31 people.*2015 ;ndash; Eight people are killed in a shooting in Harris County, Texas.Births*1079 ;ndash; Emperor Horikawa of Japan (d. 1107)*1518 ;ndash; Conrad Lycosthenes, French-German scholar and author (d. 1561)*1605 ;ndash; Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore, English lawyer and politician, Governor of Newfoundland (d. 1675)*1640 ;ndash; Amalia Catharina, German poet and composer (d. 1697)*1646 ;ndash; Godfrey Kneller, 